        <p>Holidays are where divorce and separation feel sharpest. The day you used to spend as a family is now split, scheduled, or spent apart — and the comparison game with your co-parent can quietly take over. The goal here isn't to "win" the holidays. It's to make your time with your kids genuinely good, and to get through the time without them in one piece.</p>

        <h2>Splitting the holiday schedule</h2>
        <p>Most custody arrangements address holidays specifically, because the standard week-to-week schedule doesn't cover them well. If yours doesn't, it's worth sorting before the calendar forces the issue. Common approaches:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Alternating years</strong> — one parent gets Thanksgiving in even years, the other in odd years, and so on. Simple and predictable.</li>
          <li><strong>Splitting the day</strong> — morning with one parent, afternoon/evening with the other. Works when you live close, but can make the day feel rushed for everyone.</li>
          <li><strong>Fixed assignments</strong> — each parent always has certain holidays. Useful when specific holidays matter more to one side (religious or family traditions).</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate the holiday</strong> — celebrate "Christmas" on the 24th and again on the 26th. Kids almost never object to two celebrations.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Whatever the split, <strong>get it in writing</strong> in your custody agreement so it isn't renegotiated under stress every year. See <a href="{{ '/legal/custody/' | url }}">Custody &amp; Visitation</a> for how holiday terms fit into a parenting plan.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Confirm the plan early — in writing.</strong> A short, unemotional text in early November ("Confirming I have the kids Thanksgiving Day this year, you have the weekend after — that match your calendar?") prevents the week-of conflict that ruins holidays. Calm, specific, and documented.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Making your time genuinely special</h2>
        <p>You don't need to out-spend or out-spectacle the other parent. Kids remember how a day felt, not what it cost. A few things that actually land:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Build your own traditions.</strong> Something that's just yours together — a specific breakfast, a movie, decorating in a particular way, an annual outing. Repetition is what makes kids feel anchored, and new traditions tell them this home is real and permanent.</li>
          <li><strong>Involve them in the doing,</strong> not just the receiving. Baking, wrapping, decorating, cooking the meal together — kids treasure the participation more than the polished result.</li>
          <li><strong>Lower the bar on perfection.</strong> A relaxed dad making pancakes beats a stressed dad executing a flawless holiday. They feel your mood more than your effort.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't bad-mouth the other parent,</strong> especially on these days. Let your kids love the holiday at both homes without guilt. It's one of the most protective things you can do for them.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Birthdays</h2>
        <p>Birthdays carry their own weight because they're about your child specifically. A few ways to keep them smooth:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Coordinate, don't compete.</strong> Two separate parties is fine; two competing parties the same weekend is exhausting for the kid. A quick conversation about who's doing what avoids it.</li>
          <li><strong>Be present even when it's not "your" day.</strong> If the party falls on the other parent's time and you can both be civil, showing up matters more to your kid than whose day it technically is.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep your celebration about them,</strong> not about proving anything. The point is the kid feeling celebrated, full stop.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The hard part: the days you don't have them</h2>
        <p>This is the side nobody warns you about. The house is quiet, the holiday is happening, and your kids are somewhere else. It's one of the loneliest parts of co-parenting, and it's worth having a plan for instead of white-knuckling it.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Make plans — don't sit in the empty house.</strong> Friends, family, a meal with other people, even a volunteer shift. Isolation makes it heavier.</li>
          <li><strong>Connect with other single dads.</strong> Plenty are in the exact same spot on the exact same day. The <a href="{{ '/mental/support-groups/' | url }}">Support Groups guide</a> covers communities built for this.</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule a short call or video with the kids</strong> if your arrangement allows — but keep it light and brief. A quick "love you, have fun" beats a long, sad call that makes everyone feel worse.</li>
          <li><strong>Plan your celebration with them for another day</strong> and let yourself look forward to it. The holiday isn't the date; it's the time together.</li>
          <li><strong>If the day brings you genuinely low,</strong> that's worth taking seriously — the <a href="{{ '/mental/counseling/' | url }}">Counseling guide</a> and <a href="{{ '/mental/helplines/' | url }}">Helplines</a> are there for exactly these moments.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>School events and milestones</h2>
        <p>Concerts, games, conferences, graduations — these matter to kids, and your presence registers. A few notes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Get on the school's communication list yourself</strong> so you hear about events directly, not secondhand. See <a href="{{ '/resources/childcare-school/' | url }}">Childcare &amp; School</a> for how to set that up.</li>
          <li><strong>Both parents can usually attend</strong> public events even on the other's custody time. Sit separately if needed — your kid scanning the crowd just wants to see you there.</li>
          <li><strong>Take the photo and send it</strong> to the other parent if they couldn't make it. Modeling that kind of decency teaches your kids more than any lecture.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The comparison trap is the real enemy.</strong> Holidays go sideways when they become a contest — bigger gifts, better party, favorite parent. Your kids don't need the best holiday. They need a dad who's calm, present, and clearly glad to have them. That's the version they'll remember.</p>
        </div>

        <p>For the everyday logistics underneath all of this, the <a href="{{ '/resources/' | url }}">Resources overview</a> covers food, childcare, and finding local help.</p>
